CLASS ACTION
COMPLAINT FOR VIOLATION  
OF THE FEDERAL SECURITIES 
LAWS 
  
  
  
DEMAND FOR JURY TRIAL



SUMMARY OF THE ACTION
1. This is a securities fraud class action on behalf of persons who 
purchased BroadVision, Inc. ("BroadVision" or the "Company") common stock 
between 1/26/01 and 4/2/01 (the "Class Period"), against BroadVision and 
its top officers for violations of the federal securities laws arising 
out of defendants' dissemination of false and misleading statements concerning 
the Company's 4thQ 00 financial results, the release of its new product, 
its business and its prospects for 2001 and beyond. 
2. BroadVision develops, markets and supports application software solutions 
designed for one-to-one relationship management across extended enterprises. 
These solutions are intended to enable businesses to use the Internet as 
a platform to conduct electronic commerce, provide online customer self-service, 
deliver targeted information to constituents, and provide online financial 
services. By late 2000, BroadVision's stock price had declined significantly 
due to reduced demand for its products and slowing sales. By the time BroadVision 
reported its results for the 4thQ 00 on 1/25/01, BroadVision's CEO and 
CFO were aware that the Company was suffering from a horrendous combination 
of declining demand and out of control expenses. They also knew BroadVision's 
new version of its One-to-One Enterprise product (Version 6.0), due to 
be released in the 1stQ 01, did not meet J2EE standards, which would reduce 
demand for this new product and further impact BroadVision's future results. 
Defendants knew these conditions would severely impair BroadVision's future 
revenue growth and impair their ability to make future stock sales and 
extract future bonuses which were tied to the Company's performance. Thus, 
defendants continued to make positive but false statements about BroadVision's 
business and future revenues when reporting BroadVision's 4thQ 00 results. 
As a result, BroadVision's stock traded as high as $15-3/16 during the 
Class Period. 
3. Then, on 4/2/01, after the close of market, BroadVision announced 
its preliminary 1stQ 01 results, the revision of its previously reported 
4thQ 00 results and a one-time charge in the 2ndQ 01: 
BroadVision, Inc., a leading provider of personalized e-business 
applications, today announced that, based on preliminary estimates, it 
expects revenue for the quarter ended March 31, 2001 will be between $85 
million and $90 million, and basic pro-forma loss per share, pending review 
of non-recurring items, will be in the range of $0.14 to $0.16. The Company 
believes these results were adversely affected by uncertainties surrounding 
the current economic and IT spending environments, which caused customers 
to delay purchases of the Company's products. 
As a result of these uncertainties, the Company announced it will implement 
a number of initiatives to substantially reduce its operating expenses, 
including a corporate-wide reorganization and related workforce reduction 
of approximately 325 people, or 15% of the Company's workforce. Based on 
these actions, the Company anticipates that it will record a one-time charge 
in the second quarter. An estimate of this charge will be disclosed when 
the Company reports its first quarter earnings on April 24th, 2001. 
The Company also announced it has revised its previously released, unaudited 
financial results for the fourth quarter ended December 31, 2000 to include 
approximately $4 million of additional expenses. These additional expenses 
were identified by the Company subsequent to the press release issued on 
January 25, 2001 and were promptly brought to the attention of the Company's 
independent auditors. These expenses reduced reported fourth quarter diluted 
pro-forma earnings per share to $0.01 from $0.02 and full fiscal year 2000 
pro-forma earnings per share to $0.12 from $0.13 on a fully diluted basis. 
4. This disclosure shocked the market, causing BroadVision's stock to decline 
to $2-13/16 per share before closing at $2-31/32 on 4/3/01, inflicting 
hundreds of millions of dollars of damage on plaintiff and the Class. BroadVision's 
CFO did not fair nearly so poorly, having sold 30,000 shares of his BroadVision 
stock before the bad news was revealed. 

JURISDICTION AND VENUE
5. The claims asserted herein arise under §§10(b) and 20(a) 
of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 ("1934 Act"), 15 U.S.C. §§78j(b) 
and 78t(a), and Rule 10b-5. Jurisdiction is conferred by §27 of the 
1934 Act, 15 U.S.C. §78aa. 
6. Venue is proper here pursuant to §27 of the 1934 Act. BroadVision 
is located in Redwood City, California and the acts and transactions giving 
rise to the violations of law complained of occurred here. 

THE PARTIES
7. Plaintiff Iris Hsu purchased shares of BroadVision common stock as 
detailed in the attached certification and was damaged thereby. 
8. Defendant BroadVision designs and sells software solutions to permit 
companies to use the Internet as a platform to conduct electronic commerce. 
BroadVision is headquartered in Redwood City, California. BroadVision's 
stock is traded in an efficient market on the Nasdaq National Market System. 
9. (a) Defendant Pehong Chen ("Chen") was, during the Class Period, 
Chairman of the Board, Chief Executive Officer and President of the Company. 
(b) Defendant Randall C. Bolten ("Bolten") was, during the Class Period, 
Chief Financial Officer and Executive Vice-President, Operations of the 
Company. During the Class Period Bolten sold 30,000 shares of his BroadVision 
stock for proceeds of $306,600. 
10. The parties listed in ¶9(a)-(b) are referred to as the "Individual 
Defendants." They are liable for the false statements pleaded herein at 
¶17, as those statements were each "group-published" information for 
which they were collectively responsible. The Individual Defendants, by 
reason of their stock ownership and positions with BroadVision, were controlling 
persons of BroadVision. BroadVision controlled each of the Individual Defendants. 
These controlling persons are liable under §20(a) of the 1934 Act. 

SCIENTER AND SCHEME ALLEGATIONS
11. The Individual Defendants are BroadVision's top executives. They 
ran BroadVision as "hands-on" managers, dealing with important issues facing 
BroadVision's business, i.e., its rising expenses, its new products, 
including One-to-One Enterprise Version 6.0, BroadVision's market share 
position, and its ability to report earnings in 2001 in light of the dramatic 
adverse developments which had been affecting BroadVision's business since 
late 2000. 
12. BroadVision was founded in 1993 and went public in June 1996. The 
stock did not trade above $10 per share(1) 
until late 1999 and early 2000, when the stock price increased dramatically 
to approximately $90 per share in connection with the market's appetite 
for Internet-related companies. In mid-April 2000, the NASDAQ suffered 
a significant decline and BroadVision's stock declined as well. By late 
2000, BroadVision's growth had slowed and its stock price declined even 
further. 
13. By the time BroadVision reported its results for the 4thQ 00 on 
1/25/01, BroadVision's CEO and CFO were aware that the Company was suffering 
from a horrendous combination of declining demand and out of control expenses. 
They also knew BroadVision's new version of its One-To-One Enterprise product 
(Version 6.0), due to be released in the 1stQ 01, did not meet J2EE standards, 
which would reduce demand for this new product and further impact BroadVision's 
future results. Defendants knew these conditions would severely impair 
BroadVision's future revenue growth and impair their ability to make future 
stock sales and extract future bonuses, which were tied to the Company's 
performance. 
14. BroadVision's most important new product in early 2001 was Version 
6.0, which was to be generally available in the 1stQ 01, and the Individual 
Defendants closely monitored its progress and the specifications it met. 
This new product was important to BroadVision because its competitor, Vignette, 
already had a version that was compatible with the latest version of Sun 
Microsystems' Java programming language, known as J2EE, a new language 
that was already familiar to some 2 million developers and is popular because 
it works seamlessly with other software. 
15. Also, at the time BroadVision reported its 4thQ 00 results, defendants 
were aware that expenses were much higher than the market had been led 
to expect. As a result, the Individual Defendants (particularly Bolten) 
closely scrutinized operating expenses. Nonetheless, in order to avoid 
having BroadVision's 4thQ 00 results be a complete disaster, defendants 
deliberately disregarded more than $4 million in additional expenses which 
should have been recorded in the 4thQ 00. 
16. Each of the defendants was personally familiar with BroadVision's 
1stQ 01 revenues, as they monitored BroadVision's sales, closely monitoring 
the performance of BroadVision's operations via reports from BroadVision's 
Finance and Sales Departments which were generated and provided to management 
on a weekly basis. The reports summarized orders, dollar volume and product 
type. As a result of the Individual Defendants' monitoring, each of the 
Individual Defendants was aware that BroadVision would be unable to meet 
its projected results, as its large customers were cutting back on, or 
delaying purchases. However, because the "appearance" of future earnings 
growth was so critical to defendants' plan to inflate the price of BroadVision 
shares, defendants concealed the adverse factors then affecting its business. 

FALSE AND MISLEADING STATEMENTS
DURING THE CLASS PERIOD
17. On 1/25/01, after the markets closed, BroadVision reported its 4thQ 
00 and 2000 results in a release which stated in part: 
  



Quarter  
ended 
