$ 0.03 



* * *
"It was a great year in terms of both revenues and non-financial 
measures. Q4 2000 was BroadVision's eleventh consecutive quarter of profitability, 
on a pro-forma basis. Our aggressive growth and enhanced presence in global 
markets did result in higher than anticipated expense levels in Q4, but 
we feel good about the market and believe that we are well positioned for 
continued success," said Dr. Pehong Chen, president and CEO, BroadVision. 

* * *
This past quarter, 14 leading firms joined BroadVision's expanding network 
of systems integration, consulting and reseller partners to expand its 
distribution channels, broaden product integration, and develop and launch 
new technology and services to further penetrate markets in leading industries 
worldwide. Highlights this quarter include: 

* * *
o A strategic alliance with BEA Systems to embed BEA WebLogic Server� 
within BroadVision One-To-One Enterprise, BroadVision's e-business application 
platform.... 
The announcement of this strategic alliance was included in BroadVision's 
introduction of the next generation of BroadVision's e-business application 
platform, BroadVision One-To-One Enterprise. The partnership with BEA Systems 
will add Java� 2 Platform, Enterprise Edition (J2EE�) support to BroadVision 
One-To-One Enterprise Version 6. These new Java technology-based features 
will enhance BroadVision's already robust support for open standards including 
JavaScript� technology, C++, COM, CORBA, XML, XSL, LDAP, WML and WAP. BroadVision 
One-To-One Enterprise Version 6 will be one of the only J2EE technology-compatible 
e-business solution suites to also deliver comprehensive e-business applications, 
content management, personalization, analytics and wireless support from 
a single vendor. 
18. On 1/25/01, at 4:30 p.m. (Eastern Time), BroadVision hosted a conference 
for analysts, media representatives and large BroadVision investors in 
which Chen and Bolten made statements and answered questions. During the 
call, Chen and Bolten represented that: 
o Although BroadVision had experienced higher expenses in the 
4thQ 00, it expected expenses to remain flat in the 1stQ 01, such that 
this was not a trend. 
o The Company's management was comfortable with analysts' estimates 
for revenues of $137-$140 million in the 1stQ 01 and $600-$630 million 
in 2001. 
o The higher than expected expenses were more an operational issue and 
did not impact BroadVision's growth drivers, as demand and revenue growth 
continued to be strong. 
o Revenue in the 1stQ 01 would be fueled by the general availability 
of the BroadVision/BEA Systems J2EE-compliant One-to-One Enterprise Version 
6. 
o Management was seeing continued strong demand for BroadVision's InfoExchange 
Portal and MarketMaker products. 
o Average selling price ("ASP") of BroadVision's products continued 
to increase to $470,000 in the 4thQ 00 and was increasing in the 1stQ 01 
as well. 
o BroadVision had the strongest partner relationships in the industry 
with entrenched positions with the Big 5 channel systems integrators. 
o Some of the increase in expenses in the 4thQ 00 was research and development 
costs associated with the roll-out of Version 6.0. 
o BroadVision continued to be on track to report EPS of $0.02 and $0.15+ 
in the 1stQ 01 and 2001, respectively. 
19. Analysts repeated defendants' statements in analyst reports issued 
on 1/26/01 in which analysts recommended purchase of BroadVision stock 
based on defendants' statements and forecast the following revenue and 
EPS for BroadVision: 
  


