20. The above analyst reports also stated: 
o Wit SoundView: 
[W]e are still comfortable with BroadVision's revenue growth opportunity 
because there will be an additional 31 sales representatives with three 
to six months of experience that could, in our estimation, add another 
$15 million in license software to our current estimate of $80 million 
in 1Q01. 
o Legg Mason: 
Revenue results were healthy, with strong generation from marquee customers 
and a rejuvenated product pipeline. The product pipeline, in particular, 
appears quite healthy. The company continues to indicate that market health 
is based on large deals to Fortune 1000 customers. Systems integration 
work appears to be flowing back to the Big 5, potentially away from the 
Web integrators. We believe both of those points cater to BroadVision's 
strengths within the industry. 
o USBancorp Piper: 
We believe that customers and channel partners are asking for flexible, 
extensible, and scalable solutions based on open architectures including 
Java, and that in response, BroadVision has laid the road map for a Java 
migration. By the end of the March quarter 2001, we believe that BroadVision 
will have in general availability a Java-enabled solution. We also believe 
that by the first half of 2002, BroadVision will transition to a full Java-based 
architecture. We believe that migrating to Java will provide both a more 
flexible and extensible solution for BroadVision's customers, and increased 
channel support from systems integrators and consultants. Having stated 
the benefits of this transition, we do have an elevated awareness of the 
inherent execution risks associated with this migration. We reiterate our 
Buy rating. 
o Jefferies & Co.: 
While architecture issues may become an issue with future developments, 
BVSN's move to the J2EE standard (scheduled for release at the end of March) 
should resolve any near-term concerns about integration, particularly as 
its WebLogic-compatible version becomes available at the same time. Between 
these two developments, BVSN has effectively resolved the main criticisms 
of its core technology - that it is hard to integrate and doesn't scale 
very well - through its partnerships with BEA Systems and WebMethods. What 
has not been evident, however, is BVSN's very strong position in a space 
that is widely seen to be a critical technology to enable e-business. The 
"buy vs. build" criticism strikes us as a significant advantage as the 
market migrates toward mass adopters. 
o Moors Cabot: 
With respect to BEA Systems, the two companies still need to work out 
a royalty payment that is feasible to both parties, but we understand an 
agreement is imminent. BEA will integrate its WebLogic application server 
into BroadVision's v6.0 application platform, offering BroadVision's customers 
Java functionality and J2EE compliance. 
As for version 6.0, management assured us that the Company is on track 
to deliver the product by the end of this quarter. 
o Friedman, Billings, Ramsey & Co.: 
The most significant new product, and potentially company defining, 
will be the upcoming release of Version 6. This release will embed BEA's 
WebLogic Server and provide the Java support that BVSN has been lacking. 
The few beta customers have experienced no difficulties migrating from 
previous releases, according to management. 
o Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown: 
-- Management stood firm with its 2001 revenue guidance in spite of 
only beating 4Q guidance by a hair and slightly missing our estimate. 
o J.P. Morgan: 
Management is clearly aware of the problems, and is taking a number 
of actions to address the issues, including implementing a new global accounting 
and HR system, eliminating facility, equipment and personnel redundancies, 
trimming underperforming staff and strengthening management infrastructure. 
Q1 expenses are expected to be flat to slightly improved, with the goal 
of reaching 15% operating margins by Q4, up from 3.4% this quarter. 
21. On or about 3/8/01, analyst David Hilal of Friedman, Billings, Ramsey 
& Co. met with BroadVision management (Chen) regarding the 1stQ 01 
progress. Based on this meeting, Friedman, Billings, Ramsey issued a report 
on 3/9/01 which lowered its rating on BroadVision to accumulate, but continued 
to forecast 1stQ 01 and 2001 EPS of $0.02 and $0.16, respectively, and 
stated: 
Mid-quarter update. Yesterday, we had a mid-quarter update 
with CEO Pehong Chen. We believe the company has a strong product cycle 
for this year, but that it could be overshadowed in the near-term by a 
difficult IT spending environment. 

* * *
Version 6.0 update. Management indicated that Version 6.0 is on track 
to be GA by the end of the month. This release will embed BEA's WebLogic 
Server and provide the Java support that BVSN has been lacking. Current 
beta customers have experienced no difficulties migrating from previous 
releases, according to management. Management expects that 50% of current 
customers will migrate to the new version within the first six months, 
with the balance switching over during the following six months. 
22. On 3/8/01, analyst Tim Getz of Prudential Securities also visited with 
BroadVision management. Based on this meeting, on 3/9/01, Prudential Securities 
issued a report in BroadVision which stated: 
o We visited with management of BroadVision yesterday and left 
with the several takeaways 
1) J2EE Version 6.0 is on track for commercial release by March 31, 
2001 with a majority of the horizontal and vertical 6.0 applications shipping 
by March 31 as well. IEP product remains strong. 
2) Linearity of orders in the quarter of 2001 is at or slightly below 
historical rates, 
i.e., slightly more back-end loaded. 
3) Expense controls put into place this quarter have been effective. 
4) Given the current macro economic environment, we believe it is unlikely 
that the Company will make its guidance for this quarter in this environment. 
Our estimates for the quarter are $125.2 million in revenue and ($0.01) 
in loss per share, below the Company's guidance of $137-$140 million in 
revenue and $0.02 in EPS. 
23. In early 2000, BroadVision had hired a new external auditor, Arthur 
Andersen, LLP. Arthur Andersen signed its audit report as to BroadVision's 
financial statements for 2000 on Friday, 3/30/01. Defendants knew these 
results were worse than the Company had reported on 1/25/01 due to more 
than $4 million in additional expenses BroadVision had not reported at 
that time. The Form 10-K for 2000 was signed and dated 3/30/01. Thus, by 
3/30/01 at the latest, defendants knew the truth about BroadVision's 4thQ 
earnings would have to be revealed. Nevertheless, despite having the entire 
weekend to issue a press release announcing that its previously issued 
results for the 4thQ 00 and year ended 2000 were false, defendants waited 
until after the close of the market on Monday, 4/2/01. On 4/2/01, 5.2 million 
shares of BroadVision were traded at prices between $4.34 and $5.46. 
24. Then, on 4/2/01, after the market closed, BroadVision issued a press 
release which stated: 
BroadVision, Inc., a leading provider of personalized e-business 
applications, today announced that, based on preliminary estimates, it 
expects revenue for the quarter ended March 31, 2001 will be between $85 
million and $90 million, and basic pro-forma loss per share, pending review 
of non-recurring items, will be in the range of $0.14 to $0.16. The Company 
believes these results were adversely affected by uncertainties surrounding 
the current economic and IT spending environments, which caused customers 
to delay purchases of the Company's products. 
As a result of these uncertainties, the Company announced it will implement 
a number of initiatives to substantially reduce its operating expenses, 
including a corporate-wide reorganization and related workforce reduction 
of approximately 325 people, or 15% of the Company's workforce. Based on 
these actions, the Company anticipates that it will record a one-time charge 
in the second quarter. An estimate of this charge will be disclosed when 
the Company reports its first quarter earnings on April 24th, 2001. 
The Company also announced it has revised its previously released, unaudited 
financial results for the fourth quarter ended December 31, 2000 to include 
approximately $4 million of additional expenses. These additional expenses 
were identified by the Company subsequent to the press release issued on 
January 25, 2001 and were promptly brought to the attention of the Company's 
independent auditors. These expenses reduced reported fourth quarter diluted 
pro-forma earnings per share to $0.01 from $0.02 and full fiscal year 2000 
pro-forma earnings per share to $0.12 from $0.13 on a fully diluted basis. 
25. This disclosure shocked the market, causing BroadVision's stock to 
decline to $2-13/16 per share before closing at $2-31/32 on 4/3/01, inflicting 
hundreds of millions of dollars of damage on plaintiff and the Class. BroadVision's 
CFO did not fair nearly so poorly, having sold 30,000 shares of his BroadVision 
stock before the bad news was revealed. 
26. Analysts were shocked by the extent to which BroadVision's actual 
results will miss the defendants' prior statements: 
o License revenues for the 1stQ 01 are roughly half what they 
had been led to believe just two months before. 
o Total revenues for the 1stQ 01 will be at least 35% lower than defendants' 
prior representations. 
o Instead of the $0.02 profit per share forecast for 1stQ 01, BroadVision 
will report a loss of $0.14-$0.16 per share. 
o Instead of the profit of $0.16-$0.19 forecast for 2001, analysts now 
expect BroadVision to report a loss of $0.35 to $0.54 per share. 
27. As to Version 6.0, USBancorp Piper wrote the following: 
BroadVision One-To-One Enterprise 6.0 Release - Recently Shipped 
The J2EE standard has 12 specifications that must be met in order to 
be fully compliant. BroadVision's product currently meets 2 of the 12 specifications 
and the other 10 requirements can only be met if its customers purchase 
the WebLogic application server from BEA. Because of the failure of the 
OEM agreement, after buying the 6.0 product, customers must separately 
purchase BEA's WebLogic server for a list price of $17,000 per CPU in order 
to have a fully J2EE compliant product. This may fall short of meeting 
some customer's expectations of a completely free upgrade to a J2EE compliant 
product. 
28. Each of the statements disseminated between 1/25/01 and 4/2/01 were 
false or misleading when issued. The true but concealed facts were: 
(a) BroadVision's 4thQ 00 earnings were overstated by $0.01 and were 
actually half of what BroadVision had reported, such that BroadVision had 
not met earnings estimates for the quarter. 
(b) BroadVision's 4thQ 00 operating expenses, though higher than market 
expectations, had actually been understated by $4 million, including a 
$3.3 million understatement of IT and marketing expenses and $750,000 of 
royalty payments. 
(c) BroadVision's Version 6.0 only met 2 of 12 specifications of the 
J2EE standards. Consequently, customers wishing to have a fully J2EE-compliant 
product were required to separately purchase a WebLogic server at a cost 
of $17,000 for each Version 6.0 purchased, making Version 6.0 not J2EE 
compliant and not likely to lead to the sales growth represented by defendants. 
(d) Demand for the Company's products was deteriorating rapidly and 
as a result, BroadVision's sales, particularly its license sales, were 
not on track to achieve 1stQ 01 revenues of $137 to $140 million. 
(e) Due to the above factors, defendants actually knew that there was 
virtually no way BroadVision would achieve the 1stQ 01 and 2001 revenues 
and earnings forecast by and for the Company. 

CLASS ACTION ALLEGATIONS
29. This is a class action on behalf of purchasers of BroadVision common 
stock during the Class Period, excluding defendants (the "Class"). Excluded 
from the Class are officers and directors of the Company, as well as their 
families and the families of the defendants. Class members are so numerous 
that joinder of them is impracticable. 
30. Common questions of law and fact predominate and include whether 
defendants: (i) violated the 1934 Act; (ii) omitted and/or misrepresented 
material facts; (iii) knew or recklessly disregarded that their statements 
were false; and (iv) artificially inflated BroadVision's stock price and 
the extent of and appropriate measure of damages. 
31. Plaintiff's claims are typical of those of the Class. Prosecution 
of individual actions would create a risk of inconsistent adjudications. 
Plaintiff will adequately protect the interests of the Class. A class action 
is superior to other available methods for the fair and efficient adjudication 
of this controversy. 

CLAIM FOR RELIEF
32. Defendants violated §10(b) and Rule 10b-5 by: 
(a) Employing devices, schemes and artifices to defraud; 
(b) Making untrue statements of material facts and omitting to state 
material facts necessary in order to make the statements made, in light 
of the circumstances under which they were made, not misleading; and 
(c) Engaging in acts, practices and a course of business that operated 
as a fraud or deceit upon the Class in connection with their purchases 
of BroadVision stock. 
33. Class members were damaged, as they paid artificially inflated prices 
for BroadVision common stock in reliance on the integrity of the market. 

PRAYER
WHEREFORE, plaintiff, on behalf of herself and the Class, prays for 
judgment as follows: 
A. Declaring this action to be a class action properly maintained pursuant 
to Rule 23 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure; 
B. Awarding plaintiff and other members of the Class damages together 
with interest thereon; 
C. Awarding plaintiff and other members of the Class costs and expenses 
of this litigation, including reasonable attorneys' fees, accountants' 
fees and experts' fees and other costs and disbursements; and 
D. Awarding plaintiff and other members of the Class such equitable/injunctive 
or other and further relief as may be just and proper under the circumstances. 

JURY DEMAND
Plaintiff demands a trial by jury. 
  


DATED: April 30, 2001
